{"id":"1909.05463","submitter":"Jie Xie","authors":"Jie Xie, Aonan Zhang, Ningping Cao, Huichao Xu, Kaimin Zheng, Yiu-Tung\n  Poon, Nung-Sing Sze, Ping Xu, Bei Zeng, Lijian Zhang","title":"Observing geometry of quantum states in a three-level system","comments":"14 pages, 7 figures","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. Lett. 125, 150401 (2020)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevLett.125.150401","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In quantum mechanics, geometry has been demonstrated as a useful tool for\ninferring non-classical behaviors and exotic properties of quantum systems. One\nstandard approach to illustrate the geometry of quantum systems is to project\nthe quantum state space to the Euclidean space via measurements of observables\non the system. Despite the great success of this method in studying two-level\nquantum systems (qubits) with the celebrated Bloch sphere representation, there\nis always the difficulty to reveal the geometry of multi-dimensional quantum\nsystems. Here we report the first experiment measuring the geometry of such\nprojections beyond the qubit. Specifically, we observe the joint numerical\nranges (JNRs) of a triple of observables in a three-level photonic system,\nproviding complete classification of the JNRs. We further show that the\ngeometry of different classes reveal ground-state degeneracies of a Hamiltonian\nas a linear combination of the observables, which is related to quantum phases\nin the thermodynamic limit. Our results offer a versatile geometric approach\nfor exploring the properties of higher-dimensional quantum systems.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 12 Sep 2019 05:51:19 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sun, 17 Jan 2021 13:46:38 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-01-19"}
